'The sea is ours': landlocked Bolivia hopes court will reopen a path to the Pacific
Marines patrol a corduroy-covered naval base in La Paz.
Public buildings carry a navy blue flag.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon bear the slogan: "The sea is ours by right.
To recover it is a duty".
All over landlocked Bolivia, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still alive, as is the yearning to sail the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes are perhaps at their highest point in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, a positive outlook on the outcome", said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the TIJ's ruling on giant screens scattered across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of their country's claim, so that, after decades of uncertain negotiations, Chile will be forced to negotiate, granting Bolivia a sovereign outlet to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous Bolivian president, who faces a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has much at stake in Monday's ruling.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean", was the president's vow last August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will rule in favor of Bolivia, and that little would change even if it did.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no powers to assign Chilean territory to another country and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
That the TIJ's ruling was handed down just six months after the final arguments were heard indicates that the case "wasn't complicated", said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from promoting the Bolivian cause, the last four years may have hurt it.
"The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration", Zarate said.
Morales' belligerent rhetoric has undermined some residual Chilean goodwill, he suggested.
At some point in the future, Bolivia and Chile will continue talks, but it will be extremely difficult to maintain dialogue after this.
The two countries haven't exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision-making process was unusually fast.
Next Monday will give Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of mutually beneficial disagreements", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, still one of Latin America's most popular presidents, was using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean", he added.
"The sentence is an opportunity to understand that we must move beyond the past".
