John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, and this trend continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional test results, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community initiatives.
With over 30 000 pupils spread across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to achieve the best level of service for both pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further study and university entry, as well as for their chosen career and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an education sector that is able to design and implement a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and sought-after topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you can get into his mind.
If we speak to him in his own language, we can reach his heart".
This quote reminds us that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of the recent examinations this year, we find that languages are at the top of the table, with the highest utilization rates in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the maximum A rating.
This data, collected from the 74 schools under the SCIS, shows that 72% of pupils achieved the highest A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that Scottish independent schools are favouring foreign languages as vital skills that will unquestionably serve children and young people in the future.
Languages as an option are now treated in the same way as STEM subjects in the curricula of independent schools and beyond.
A survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17% of the reasons why employers have difficulty filling jobs were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, knowledge of other languages is increasingly an imperative in preparing the younger generation for their future careers.
With more potential job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a tangible advantage in the future with a life skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, with French being the only language spoken by a two-digit proportion, 15%.
So investing now in language learning is important for today's children.
The proficiency in several languages, particularly those of developing countries, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Some will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be the most important for the UK by the 2020 horizon, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a language set of choice in independent schools, supported by teaching staff who are specialists in the field.
Scottish Independent Schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may hold.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalised business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance for the future of the country.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "skills of international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer this option with diversity and excellence to young Scots.
It must be done well.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
