North Korea says "not even thinking" of unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continuation of sanctions was exacerbating mistrust of the United States and that there was no way the country could unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" in the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test center and committing to nonproliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we do not see any corresponding response from the US", he said.
"Without trust in the United States there will be no trust in our national security and under such circumstances there is no way we can proceed to our disarmament first".
While Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statements appear to be significant in that they do not reject unilateral denuclearization outright, in contrast to Pyongyang's previous positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work toward the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump offered security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States insists that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
'The United States insists on 'denuclearisation first' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its objective in a coercive manner, opposing even the 'declaration of the end of war,'' said Ri.
"The realization that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the prolongation of sanctions is exacerbating our distrust.'
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the US leader at the United Nations earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, adding: "If the interested party in this issue were South Korea and not the US, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this deadlock".
Still, the tone of Ri's speech was drastically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that directing North Korean rockets toward US territory was inevitable after "Mr. President Evil" Trump called Kim the "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year had threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, lavished praise on Kim for his courage in taking steps toward disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for such a move, saying "whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously until denuclearization is complete, final and verifiable".
The Security Council unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea imposed since 2006 in an attempt to stifle funding for North Korea's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later stated that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but the last visit didn't go well.
