At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile facility and also a nuclear complex if the United States "takes corresponding measures".
Pompeo said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" they sought were Trump's security assurances in Singapore, as well as initiatives toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course that teaches them to rest properly
A new course at Harvard University this year put all its students to sleep more, in an effort to combat the machismo culture of studying on caffeinated "straights".
One professor found that students at this world-class university often had no idea about the most basic concepts of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration for this course came after I gave a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end, a girl came to me and said, "Why are you only telling me this in my last year?"
The young woman claimed that no one had ever mentioned to her the importance of sleep, which surprised me", she told The Telegraph.
The course, first taught this year, explains key concepts about how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance as well as to improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the school decided to introduce the course after finding that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section is a picture of a dormitory where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, slippers and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and about how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation may increase the risks of stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know it's not going to change student behavior instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as we all have a right to know the health effects of the choice to smoke", added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in "doing straight" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students makes this a growing problem.
Ensuring that we get enough and quality sleep should be a "secret weapon" for students to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said, and even to prevent getting fat, since sleep deprivation puts the brain in hunger mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of physical biology and chemistry, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year as a freshman at Harvard.
The course opened his eyes and inspired him to encourage the creation of a campus-wide course, he said.
The next step, according to their expectations, is to ask all postgraduate students to attend a similar programme of study before entering the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider using a bedtime alarm as well as a wake-up call, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" from electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt circadian rhythms and lead to sleep problems.
