Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from our Sunday Morning Almanac: On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today and counting... the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A staple of science ever since, the Geiger counter has also become a staple of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado" starring the unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms released by radioactivity in the minerals".
Evans: "Look, now it's really creeping!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that gave it its name still stands.
New cancer vaccine teaches the immune system to "see" harmful cells
A new cancer vaccine teaches the immune system to "see" harmful cells and kill them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells as part of the treatment.
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient and changing them in a laboratory.
These cells, which can "see" a protein common to many cancers, are then injected back into the body.
An experimental vaccine is producing promising results in patients with a range of cancers.
One woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for over 18 months.
The method involves taking immune cells from a patient and changing them in the lab so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2.
