HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China announced a 14 percent jump in the number of its citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected in the country, health officials said.
Some 40 000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
The vast majority of new cases result from transmission through sexual intercourse, marking a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly in parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
However, the number of people who have contracted HIV in this way has been reduced to virtually zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, in terms of year-on-year variation, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100 000 people.
HIV transmission through sexual intercourse is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT community is said to be frequent.
Studies have estimated that because of the country's conservative values, 70 to 90 percent of men who have had sex with other men end up marrying women.
Many of the diseases are transmitted through inadequate sexual protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medication as part of an effort to solve the problem.
