What is the Global Citizen Festival? Did it do anything to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York City will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event with an extremely impressive roster of stars who will perform on an equally impressive mission: eradicating poverty in the world.
Now in its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will welcome tens of thousands of people to the Great Lawn of Central Park, not only to see performances by the likes of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness of the true purpose of the event: to eradicate extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, started in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an advocacy group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To receive a free ticket to the event (unless they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket), the spectators had to perform a series of tasks, or "actions", such as volunteering, sending an email to a world leader, a phone call, or any other meaningful ways that contribute to raising awareness for the goal of ending poverty.
However, how successful has Global Citizen been in these 12 years in achieving its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a genuine way to persuade them to demand action, or is this just another case of "clicktivism" - do we think it makes a difference to sign an online petition or send a tweet?
Global Citizen claims that since 2011, it has recorded more than 19 million "actions" by its supporters that have pressed for a number of different goals.
These actions, according to the organization, have contributed to world leaders announcing commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion that will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements arising from its shares, with at least $10 billion of those commitments or announcements already disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that the funds obtained have so far had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people around the world.
Some of the major commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based partnership bringing together investors and implementers committed to "helping children reach their full potential", which has pledged $35 million to Rwanda to help end malnutrition in the country, after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens like all of us, we can make the social injustice of undernutrition a footnote of history", Tracey Ullman, ambassador for The Power of Nutrition, told a crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5000 lobbying actions on the UK to improve maternal and child nutrition, the government announced that it would fund a project, Power of Nutrition, which will cover 5 million women and children with nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the website, "What makes you think we can eradicate extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen responds: "It's been a long and winding road - sometimes we've fallen and failed.
But like the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements that came before us, because we are more powerful together.
