The only Church of England clergyman to receive the Victoria Cross during the First World War as a combatant has been honoured in his home town 100 years later.
Lieutenant Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann was awarded the medal on 29 September 1918 for the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later and never knew he had received Britain's highest military honour.
His two grandchildren unveiled a commemorative plaque at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of them, Michael Vann, stated that it was "brilliantly symbolic" that the plaque had been presented exactly 100 years after the event that gave his grandfather the award.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Saint-Quentin Canal "in very thick fog and under close fire from handguns and machine guns".
He then ran to the line of fire and, "with the greatest courage", led the line forward before single-handedly attacking a cannon and shooting down three soldiers from the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "something I know I could never match, but also a lesson in humility".
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, laid a wreath after the parade, led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann stated that he "felt very honoured to participate in the parade" and added that "the courage of a genuine hero is being demonstrated through the support that will be given by many people".
