New German warship once again delayed
The latest German navy frigate was supposed to enter service in 2014 to replace Cold War-era warships, but it will have to wait at least until next year due to malfunctioning systems and an exponentially growing cost, according to local media.
The entry into service of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the flagship of the newest Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit citing a military spokesman.
The vessel was due to join the navy in 2014, but troubling post-delivery problems have undermined the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels that the navy had ordered in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is known that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, in addition to a number of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies such as reducing radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer periods between maintenance which would allow the latest frigates to be sent on missions of up to two years' duration away from home ports.
However, continuing delays have meant that the state-of-the-art warships, seen as a way for Germany to project power across borders, will be outdated by the time they enter service, reports Die Zeit.
The ill-fated F125 made headlines last year when the German Navy refused to put it into service, returning it to the Blohm & Voss shipyards in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned a ship to the shipyard after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media cite a number of crucial "hardware and software flaws" that would render the warship useless if used on a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly significant, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half the quota needed on the older Bremen class frigates.
It was also reported that the vessel is overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the navy's ability to install additional functionalities in the future.
The 7,000-tonne Rhineland-Palatinate is thought to weigh twice as much as similar class ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the hardware failures, the cost of the entire project, including crew training, is also becoming a problem.
It is said that this will have reached a staggering €3.1 billion, an increase from the €2.2 billion originally budgeted.
The problems plaguing the latest frigates have become particularly important in the light of recent warnings that German naval power is weakening.
Earlier this year Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliamentary committee on defence, acknowledged that the navy is currently running out of ships capable of being used".
The politician said the problem grew exponentially over time as older ships were taken out of service without any vessels to replace them.
In the end, he regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could join the navy.
National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research is being conducted on a farm in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use the landscape to search for food.
The results are expected to shed some light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and fruit bats, as well as long-eared brown and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations throughout the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
Mobile studies will also be carried out by NTS staff and volunteers with portable detectors.
Expert analysis of all the recordings will assess the frequency of the bats' calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviour at territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands, as well as the best way to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development work that affects the dorms and makes habitat scarce.
Wind turbines and lightning are also a threat, along with fly-killing papers and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
It is they who use a sophisticated technique of echo tracking to identify insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained specialists who regularly conduct studies, inspections of dormitories, and sometimes rescues.
It also created the first bat-only reserve in Scotland, at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten Scottish bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says it's the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Threave we have an excellent bat area", he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of old trees and all this good habitat.
However, there is still much we don't know about bats, so the work we've done here and at other properties will help us learn more about what they need to thrive".
He stressed the importance of checking for bats before any maintenance on the property, as the unintentional destruction of just one maternity dormitory could lead to the deaths of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their dormitories.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish chair of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to get involved and help.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we simply don't know how their populations are taking revenge".
