Red Tide Updates: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there has been a decline in Red Tide concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
FWC reported that conditions of lower spot proliferation were identified in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Tide Spot stretches about 201 kilometers along the coast, from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
Red tide was also spotted in Pasco County.
In the past week, there have been average concentrations off or near the coast of Pinella County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, low to high concentrations in Manatee County, low to high concentrations off or near the coast of Sarasota County, low to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, low to high concentrations off or near the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritations in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
For the past week, there have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwest region of Florida.
